In this PR, If the user wants to get an object by `ray.get` after the `creator` died, they should make sure the owner has a reference to the object.

It looks like  `creator` doesn't tell `owner` the object borrowing to `borrower`, cause `creator` is not the owner of the object (In function [CoreWorker::AllocateReturnObject](https://github.com/ray-project/ray/blob/master/src/ray/core_worker/core_worker.cc#L2043)) 

But this seems to be intuitive, this can be seen as `owner` created the object and send it to `creator`, and cleared its own reference， just like:
```python
import ray
ray.init()
@ray.remote
class A:
    def __init__(self):
        self.ref=None
    def x(self, b):
        aa = ray.put("test")
        print(aa)
        #self.ref = aa
        b.x.remote([aa])

@ray.remote
class B:
    def __init__(self):
        self.ref = None
    def x(self, x=None):
        if x:
            self.ref = x
            return x
        return self.ref
@ray.remote
class C:
    def x(self, x):
        return x
a = A.remote(); b = B.remote(); c = C.remote();
ray.get(a.x.remote(b))
data = ray.get(c.x.remote(b.x.remote()))
print("res: ", ray.get(data))
ray.kill(b)
from time import sleep; sleep(10)
print("res: ", ray.get(data))
```
and it will got `ObjectLostError` after `b` be killed.

